<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFFFFCE2FFF77FEC1DA513D04" bold="true" box="[136,258,272,298]" pageId="114" pageNumber="115">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males of 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFFFFCE2FFE88FEC0D9173D04" authorityName="Rios-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff" authorityYear="2018" box="[375,580,272,299]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="114" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="septemtrionalis">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFFFFCE2FFE88FEC0D9173D04" box="[375,580,272,299]" italics="true" pageId="114" pageNumber="115">A. septemtrionalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="E54DDF8DFFFFCE2FFDACFEC0DA683D7C" author="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A." pageId="114" pageNumber="115" pagination="1 - 83" refId="ref140496" refString="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A. (2018) Taxonomic revision and morphology of the trapdoor spider genus Actinopus (Mygalomorphae: Actinopodidae) in Argentina. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 419, 1 - 83. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 - 419.1.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Ríos-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff, 2018</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 8 G–I) resemble 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFFFFCE2FFDBCFEE9D9EA3D7F" authorityName="Rios-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff" authorityYear="2018" box="[579,697,311,338]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="114" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="clavero">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFFFFCE2FFDBCFEE9D9EA3D7F" box="[579,697,311,338]" italics="true" pageId="114" pageNumber="115">A. clavero</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Ríos-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff, 2018, fig. 4 E–G) by the elongated shape of the copulatory bulb, but males differ by the more developed PA, PA continuous to PAc and a wider angle of embolar curvature. Females of 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFFFFCE2FFE12FE05D9E83DC0" authorityName="Rios-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff" authorityYear="2018" box="[493,699,468,494]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="114" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="septemtrionalis">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFFFFCE2FFE12FE05D9E83DC0" box="[493,699,468,494]" italics="true" pageId="114" pageNumber="115">A. septemtrionalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Ríos-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff, 2018, fig. 9 D–E) have unilobate receptacles and differ from those of all other species by having the receptacles much more longer than wide (two or more times).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
